# JavaScript / JSX

## Style

- Prefer modern ES modules (`import`/`export`); match the project's module system when it differs
- Prefer `const`/`let` — never `var`; prefer `const` unless reassignment is required
- Prefer template literals over string concatenation (same spirit as Python f-strings)
- Use strict equality (`===` / `!==`)
- Document with JSDoc on every module, class, function, and exported symbol; include `@param`, `@returns`, and `@throws` when relevant (Google-style spirit)
- Prefer explicit types in JSDoc (`@param {string} id`, `@returns {Promise<User>}`) — full typing via JSDoc when TypeScript isn't in play
- Lint/format with ESLint (and Prettier if the repo uses it); match existing config and do not fight it
- Use `npm` for packaging/installs; do not introduce another package manager unless the repo already uses one
- Invoke Node as `node` (and package scripts via `npm`); prefer project scripts over ad-hoc global tools

## Docs & comments

- Every module, class, function, and React component gets a JSDoc block (purpose + params/returns/throws as applicable)
- File-level JSDoc at the top describing what the module owns
- Comments only where intent is non-obvious — never narrate what the code already says

```javascript
/**
 * Load a user by ID from the directory service.
 *
 * @param {string} userId - Stable external identifier for the user.
 * @returns {Promise<User>} The matching user record.
 * @throws {UserNotFoundError} If no user exists for `userId`.
 * @throws {DirectoryError} If the directory service is unreachable.
 */
export async function fetchUser(userId) {
  ...
}
```

## Structure & architecture

Write organized, refactored code from the first draft — do not leave monoliths “to clean up later.”

- One public function/component should do one job. If it orchestrates several steps, extract helpers (prefer non-exported functions in the same module or small collaborators)
- Prefer several small, focused units over one large function that mixes concerns (I/O, parsing, business rules, UI)
- Prefer a sensible folder layout by responsibility over a single large `.js` / `.jsx` file
- Default: one primary export per module (one component or one class). Keep additional exports in the same file only when tightly coupled
- Group related modules into folders; gather shared utilities where they belong — avoid both scatter and dumping grounds
- Be reasonable: don’t create empty layers or one-line files for their own sake; split when a file or function has more than one clear responsibility

## JSX

- Prefer function components over class components
- Keep components focused; pull hooks, handlers, and presentational pieces into helpers or child components when the file grows
- Props are part of the public contract — document them with JSDoc/`@param` (or PropTypes if the project already uses them)
- Prefer composition over prop drilling through deep trees when a clearer structure exists
- Keep JSX readable: extract conditional chunks and mapped lists into named helpers or components when inline logic gets noisy

## Robustness

- Throw specific `Error` subclasses (or project error types); never empty `catch` or swallow failures silently; prefer `cause` when rethrowing
- Prefer plain objects with a clear shape, or classes, over ad-hoc bags of fields passed everywhere
- Validate untrusted input at boundaries (API handlers, form submit, URL/query params)
- Prefer `async`/`await` over raw promise chains; always handle rejections
- Prefer structured logging over `console.log` in app/library code when a logger exists; otherwise keep console use intentional and temporary
- Always write unit tests in the same change as the code (not as a follow-up). Aim for as close to 100% coverage as practical on new/changed code so we can test and iterate fast. This is not strict TDD — implement and test together. Use the project's runner if present (`jest`, `vitest`, etc.); skip only if no test runner is available
